WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:26.000
Today is Wednesday, April 27, 2011. We're in Atlanta, Georgia, the Artmore Hotel, with Ms. Jamila Jones,

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:37.000
to conduct an oral history for the Smithsonian's National Museum of African American History and Culture project entitled The Civil Rights History Project.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:45.000
My name is Joe Mosnier of the Southern oral history program at UNC Chapel Hill and our videographer is Mr. John Bishop.

00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:47.000
Ms. Jones, good morning. Thanks so much for sitting there.

00:00:47.000 --> 00:00:48.000
Thank you for having me.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:49.000
Thank you for having me.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:55.000
Appreciate your effort to get up with us during this Atlanta visit. It's really nice to see you. Thank you.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:06.000
Let me start today as we enter into a conversation about your work and Southern freedom movement in the 50s, 60s and even thereafter.

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:15.000
Talk a little bit about your family, start with a little bit about growing up in Montgomery and your family, your parents.

00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:34.000
Okay, I live with a mother and a grandmother. I grew up with a sibling, my sister, Dars, Khrinshaw, and a brother, a little younger, about 10 years younger, John, Alan McQuirell.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:47.000
And I guess key to the movement is the fact that my sister and I rode the Montgomery bus line.

00:01:47.000 --> 00:02:00.000
So we experienced on a daily basis during school the harassment that came from the bus driver.

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:12.000
And so I guess that inspired us or it was something in us that made us relate to, of course, the Montgomery Bus Boycott.

00:02:12.000 --> 00:02:22.000
Can you talk a little bit about how you came to know Ms. Parks and to join the Youth Chapter of the Logon ACP?

00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:34.000
Yes, in fact, my sister was the one who introduced me to Mrs. Rosa Parks as we joined the NAACP Youth Council and NACP Youth Group.

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:42.000
My sister was vice president. I was just a member of that group. She would have us into her home.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:49.000
We would sit on the floor and she'd give us bits and pieces about life, actually.

00:02:49.000 --> 00:03:04.000
And people asked quite often, if I remember things that she said and I do not, but I know she read from papers from the National Office of the NAACP.

00:03:04.000 --> 00:03:11.000
And she taught us that we were important. I can remember that.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:25.000
And that it was key that we learned our rights and that voting was an important aspect of our lives.

00:03:25.000 --> 00:03:31.000
And I can just remember those things about the conversations that she had with us.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:45.000
And she also taught us that it was important to carry yourself in a good, responsible way.

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:52.000
After we were meet, she would give us Kool-Aid and Kool-Aid.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:58.000
Dr. Joe Kool-Aid was from SIRM.

00:03:58.000 --> 00:04:05.000
Ms. Jones, you mentioned your sister, Doris Ketchock. Can you talk a little bit about her? You mentioned she was vice president and just described her a little bit.

00:04:05.000 --> 00:04:13.000
Yes, she was like a leader of the bunch. And whatever she did, basically I did.

00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:21.000
There was a difference in us and that I was mostly interested in the music portion of things that happened.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:28.000
And she was more of the leadership fighter type movement person.

00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:40.000
But she somehow had interest from a very young age in rights and what was right for you.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:43.000
And she let me down that path.

00:04:43.000 --> 00:04:48.000
So you must have been about 11 years old when the boy cut began.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:51.000
How was he 11 years old when the boy cut stopped?

00:04:51.000 --> 00:05:01.000
What are some of your, you know, from this distance? What are your some of your most, most central, important memories from that experience?

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:20.000
From that experience, I know that the youth, and this is not often said, had their own kind of individual movement, that we let ourselves around what was happening with the movement.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:29.000
And that we organized ourselves to get across what we call a cross town when we were no longer riding the buses.

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:34.000
And we had to find our own way for survival.

00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:40.000
My sister being the leader that she was wouldn't allow us ever to go and get a ride.

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:48.000
She said, we'd be taking a space from an adult and we were going to walk.

00:05:48.000 --> 00:05:57.000
So the 381 days, we walked.

00:05:57.000 --> 00:06:11.000
When the boy cut concluded and some measure of success was realized in some measure on that narrow question of buzzing.

00:06:11.000 --> 00:06:15.000
What was your feeling?

00:06:15.000 --> 00:06:18.000
It was a joyous feeling of course.

00:06:18.000 --> 00:06:23.000
And no longer we felt that we had to take the abuse.

00:06:23.000 --> 00:06:28.000
That we had experienced on those buses since I was six years old.

00:06:28.000 --> 00:06:36.000
Because I started to ride the bus at age six and had done that to age 11.

00:06:36.000 --> 00:06:41.000
And we found always to survive through that.

00:06:41.000 --> 00:06:54.000
It was piercing to see adults have to leave the bus and go around to pay their money and then get off the bus and come to the back of the bus.

00:06:54.000 --> 00:07:00.000
I almost never had to do that because we were the first stop.

00:07:00.000 --> 00:07:04.000
So we always found ourselves with a seat.

00:07:04.000 --> 00:07:14.000
But curious as we were, there were times we tested to see what would happen if we sat in the front of the bus.

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:16.000
And we did.

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:24.000
And then they would ask us of course, when one white lady got on the bus I can never forget her.

00:07:24.000 --> 00:07:28.000
She had read her long hair.

00:07:28.000 --> 00:07:40.000
And when she entered the bus we would have to get up even though there were a number of seats and she was the only white to get on that bus.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:47.000
So I think there was so piercing to us that it never, I never forgot it.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:53.000
And when the bus boy caught started of course that lived within me.

00:07:53.000 --> 00:07:56.000
And I knew that I would walk 300 no hell.

00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:01.000
However many days actually that it would take.

00:08:01.000 --> 00:08:11.000
And to a six-year-old you just basically had so curious about why is it that we have to get up.

00:08:11.000 --> 00:08:14.000
That often I would sit behind her.

00:08:14.000 --> 00:08:19.000
And she would choose the same seat each time she got on the bus.

00:08:19.000 --> 00:08:25.000
And this white woman, I don't know her name, I just remember her face and her red hair.

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:32.000
But when she got on the bus I decided several times to just feel her hair.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:39.000
See if I could put my little fingers on the top of the seat to see if it was a difference.

00:08:39.000 --> 00:08:43.000
What is the difference with her and the rest of us.

00:08:43.000 --> 00:08:49.000
And I did. I would just kind of feel that hair like it was an accident.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:52.000
I don't know what I concluded from that.

00:08:52.000 --> 00:08:59.000
Except that it just gave me a feeling that I feel she's really no different.

00:08:59.000 --> 00:09:03.000
This hair is not so much different from ours.

00:09:03.000 --> 00:09:10.000
And that was just my little child who would curiosity and how I answered it.

00:09:10.000 --> 00:09:24.000
So that just that one white lady puts such curiosity in me.

00:09:24.000 --> 00:09:33.000
And I wanted to answer that so much that I knew that I was going to walk the length of the time

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:38.000
and take for us to get to our goal.

00:09:38.000 --> 00:09:41.000
When and how did you start singing?

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:51.000
Started singing. We were elementary school students at Alabama State Laboratory High School.

00:09:51.000 --> 00:10:02.000
And each Friday we would have a I would call it a talent show.

00:10:03.000 --> 00:10:09.000
And we formed this group, three girls, and she was four of us from the beginning.

00:10:09.000 --> 00:10:17.000
Form this group so that we couldn't compete each Friday in the talent contest.

00:10:17.000 --> 00:10:24.000
Somehow it was something in us that made us want to do freedom songs.

00:10:25.000 --> 00:10:33.000
And I can't answer today why we chose that because we're about the same age as Diana Ross.

00:10:33.000 --> 00:10:39.000
But when we went outside to practice, we practiced freedom songs.

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:42.000
And that's what we would sing.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:51.000
So when the Montgomery Bus Boycott came, we formed this group at around the age of 19.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:54.000
We were kind of ready.

00:10:54.000 --> 00:11:00.000
And so because of the songs we were singing, it led itself to the movement.

00:11:00.000 --> 00:11:08.000
We were asked to come to sing at practically every tea that was held in Montgomery.

00:11:08.000 --> 00:11:13.000
You know during that time they had a lot of teas that raised money for the movement

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:17.000
as well as other things for the churches.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:20.000
And they would invite us to come.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:25.000
And I felt like it couldn't be a tea.

00:11:25.000 --> 00:11:29.000
Or they felt like they couldn't have a tea if we didn't come.

00:11:29.000 --> 00:11:34.000
So we went all over town to teas on Sunday to participate.

00:11:34.000 --> 00:11:41.000
And we were kind of carrying the message of the movement through our songs.

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:44.000
And we were relevant for the time.

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:46.000
And that's why they called on us.

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:49.000
And it was a group of four girls all 11 and 12 years old I guess.

00:11:49.000 --> 00:11:52.000
We were in that moment.

00:11:52.000 --> 00:11:55.000
Do you remember the names of the other girls?

00:11:55.000 --> 00:11:56.000
I do.

00:11:56.000 --> 00:11:58.000
It was Gladys Carter.

00:11:58.000 --> 00:12:04.000
Because we formed the group and we all through high school, we kept the group.

00:12:04.000 --> 00:12:10.000
Gladys Carter and many Hendrix now McCans.

00:12:11.000 --> 00:12:17.000
We were three girls who lasted among the four.

00:12:17.000 --> 00:12:24.000
We decided we were going to not only practice at school, but we would practice at each other's homes.

00:12:24.000 --> 00:12:31.000
And that's how the fourth girl dropped out because her parents wouldn't allow her to come each evening.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:34.000
Or the evenings that we had set for practice.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:38.000
And thus it became the fourth.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:41.000
Did you all say singing church?

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:42.000
We did.

00:12:42.000 --> 00:12:44.000
We were singing church.

00:12:44.000 --> 00:12:51.000
But mostly we sang at school at first because we all went to different churches.

00:12:51.000 --> 00:12:52.000
Which was in church?

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:58.000
Mine was Mount Zion AME Zion Church.

00:12:58.000 --> 00:13:03.000
Was any of the other girls at Reverend King's church?

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:08.000
None of us were members of Reverend King's church.

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:13.000
Many McCans was a member of Reverend Abernathy's church.

00:13:13.000 --> 00:13:23.000
I was with Reving Sey, Sey, who was...

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:27.000
had the first meeting for the Montgomery Bus Boycott.

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:30.000
And he was very active.

00:13:30.000 --> 00:13:35.000
As a matter of fact, the things in your life that caused you to...

00:13:35.000 --> 00:13:39.000
I guess these some total of things caused you to be what?

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:41.000
Whatever you are in life.

00:13:41.000 --> 00:13:52.000
And he talked each Sunday about accomplishments they had made to what needs of the black community.

00:13:52.000 --> 00:13:55.000
And I would hear what he had to say.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:14:03.000
So that was one of the influences that I had in terms of my life and fighting for freedom of struggle.

00:14:03.000 --> 00:14:04.000
Yeah.

00:14:04.000 --> 00:14:13.000
Let's see, you must have entered high school around 57, 50, fall of 57, fall of 58.

00:14:13.000 --> 00:14:16.000
Yeah, I finished in 62.

00:14:17.000 --> 00:14:21.000
And can you describe the...

00:14:21.000 --> 00:14:24.000
I think the late 50s, because at some point, if...

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:30.000
I've read a couple different accounts, but one indicates that you traveled to Highlander Book School.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:31.000
I did.

00:14:31.000 --> 00:14:36.000
But that was before high school, it was like junior high school, I think, well.

00:14:36.000 --> 00:14:44.000
But I was singing along with my sister being very active.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:51.000
We were selected to go to do a kind of a cultural exchange in terms of our music.

00:14:51.000 --> 00:14:57.000
We would share the kind of songs that we would sing and got carried away.

00:14:57.000 --> 00:15:00.000
I headed up that...

00:15:00.000 --> 00:15:02.000
The workshops.

00:15:02.000 --> 00:15:09.000
And people from around the world, actually, because we met people from Africa there,

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:13.000
would share the kind of movement songs they were doing.

00:15:14.000 --> 00:15:22.000
It was because our repertoire of songs, of freedom songs, were great and extensive

00:15:22.000 --> 00:15:35.000
that we come to New York to do freedom songs, to raise money,

00:15:36.000 --> 00:15:43.000
to raise money, to raise money, to raise money, to raise money, to raise money.

00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:50.000
And that's how we got to kind of get home with Reverend Sheldon's work and others to do that fundraiser.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:16:04.000
And from that came one of the first albums of civil rights songs to be used for fundraising and that kind of thing.

00:16:04.000 --> 00:16:10.000
We were the Montgomery Gospel Trio.

00:16:10.000 --> 00:16:12.000
We did not have a name.

00:16:12.000 --> 00:16:15.000
We went all over Montgomery before that time.

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:17.000
Never thought about a name.

00:16:17.000 --> 00:16:19.000
They would just say the girls.

00:16:19.000 --> 00:16:22.000
We got to have the girls or the girls this.

00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:27.000
And when we got there, they said, for this album, you got to have a name.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:34.000
And we debated and debate about what could be our name and came up with the Montgomery Gospel Trio.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:37.000
How long have you been at that time when you went to New York?

00:16:37.000 --> 00:16:41.000
I want to say, you know, around 16.

00:16:41.000 --> 00:16:43.000
Just in high school.

00:16:43.000 --> 00:16:45.000
Yes.

00:16:45.000 --> 00:16:56.000
Can you talk me through your high school years because obviously the movement will shift and go very active days while you were in high school?

00:16:56.000 --> 00:17:04.000
The Freedom Riders will come into being toward the end of your high school years.

00:17:04.000 --> 00:17:09.000
So I'm interested in how you move through those years singing, protesting as an active event.

00:17:09.000 --> 00:17:25.000
Yes. And what happened is that Montgomery, when you have a large scale movement like that, quite often, there are a lot of wounds that occur.

00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:42.000
So, Montgomery, particularly the adults, could not sit down sometimes in the same room, let alone talk about a movement.

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:46.000
And so the youth will use.

00:17:46.000 --> 00:17:55.000
So when James Bevel and all the people came into Montgomery and by the way we did meet James Bevel and Bernard LaFayette Jr Jr,

00:17:55.000 --> 00:18:03.000
well, the other group that came to do the concert at Carnegie Hall, so we had already met them.

00:18:03.000 --> 00:18:12.000
But they came into Montgomery first with the Freedom Riders.

00:18:13.000 --> 00:18:32.000
And so because we knew them, we had gone to Reverend Ralph Abernathy's house and waiting to get the youth to go pick up the Freedom Riders as they came in because at the time we still active in movement and still singing.

00:18:32.000 --> 00:18:38.000
And Mrs. Juanita Abernathy said, we don't have anybody to pick them up.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:49.000
Now, a lot of adults will tell you that they did, but that day we stole a car. We said, well, we got to go find a way to get the Freedom Riders.

00:18:49.000 --> 00:18:56.000
And there was a girl, her name was Antoinette Carson, and she had her license at the time.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:02.000
And her grandfather would leave his car in the garage every day.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:10.000
So we skinned together and said, we were going to steal his car and go pick up the Freedom Riders.

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:14.000
And we did, it was how and the real, we're going to get this car back in here.

00:19:14.000 --> 00:19:24.000
So what we did was we took some school chalk and mark where the tires of his car were.

00:19:24.000 --> 00:19:36.000
And took the car, picked up the Freedom Riders, went back and put that car right in the tracks of those marks that we had made.

00:19:36.000 --> 00:19:48.000
And it was such an eventful day to see how they were beaten and how they were treated when getting off of those buses.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:54.000
And we had a car load up when we left.

00:19:54.000 --> 00:20:05.000
Were you yourself ever so close to violence that you really feel feared for your own personal safety?

00:20:05.000 --> 00:20:16.000
It's something about youth that even when you have fear, and it's something about having lived that kind of life,

00:20:16.000 --> 00:20:20.000
that your fear is bundled and it's there.

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:31.000
But it does not outweigh the need to participate.

00:20:31.000 --> 00:20:36.000
So that there were times when we feared, we had fear.

00:20:36.000 --> 00:20:44.000
In fact, the night that the Freedom Riders came in, we went to the church carrying them to the church.

00:20:44.000 --> 00:20:48.000
And we were there for the mass meeting that night.

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:54.000
And when we went in, there were no whites.

00:20:54.000 --> 00:21:02.000
When we sat there while the church was completely surrounded, as far as you could see,

00:21:02.000 --> 00:21:14.000
white, mostly males on horses and carrying long guns and sitting outside waiting on us to come out.

00:21:14.000 --> 00:21:21.000
And that was the night that we in fact spent the night at the church.

00:21:21.000 --> 00:21:33.000
So it was a fear for night, but not enough fear to stop us from doing what we needed to do.

00:21:33.000 --> 00:21:43.000
I was just going to say that Reverend Solomon S. Seay Sr said that night to me, we were eating some food, had come in, sandwiches, and that kind of thing.

00:21:43.000 --> 00:21:47.000
And he was sitting on the steps at the church on the inside.

00:21:47.000 --> 00:21:51.000
And I said, Reverend, say, what are we going to do?

00:21:51.000 --> 00:21:57.000
Because as far as we could see, all these people surrounding us.

00:21:57.000 --> 00:22:04.000
And he said, we're going to do like the doodle bird.

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:07.000
And I said, what do you mean?

00:22:07.000 --> 00:22:08.000
He said, doodle bird?

00:22:08.000 --> 00:22:10.000
Because he called me doodle bird quite a bit.

00:22:10.000 --> 00:22:12.000
We're going to do like the doodle bird.

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:19.000
And I was an adult before I really understood what we were saying, but we played this game in Montgomery.

00:22:19.000 --> 00:22:23.000
And we were seeing the doodle bird song.

00:22:23.000 --> 00:22:27.000
And we said, back, back, doodle, back, back.

00:22:27.000 --> 00:22:31.000
Your house is on fire.

00:22:31.000 --> 00:22:35.000
Your children's burning.

00:22:35.000 --> 00:22:40.000
Back, go back, doodle, back, back.

00:22:40.000 --> 00:22:46.000
And I had to think about it as I became an adult because I really didn't know at the time what he was saying.

00:22:46.000 --> 00:22:48.000
I thought about how that song said.

00:22:48.000 --> 00:22:51.000
Your house is on fire and you're in trouble.

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:54.000
But you're going to be just like the doodle bird.

00:22:54.000 --> 00:22:59.000
And the doodle bird, when we were singing that song, the doodle bird, with back,

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:03.000
just back out of the sand.

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:13.000
And he was so small, but as if to say, I'm protecting my own.

00:23:13.000 --> 00:23:17.000
It's possible, excuse me, just one second.

00:23:17.000 --> 00:23:19.000
We're back after short break.

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:25.000
Can you tell me about the founding of the Freedom Singers?

00:23:25.000 --> 00:23:32.000
Well, actually, the Freedom Singers is, as you know them, I was not a part of that group.

00:23:32.000 --> 00:23:36.000
I joined after leaving the Montgomery Gospel Trio.

00:23:36.000 --> 00:23:46.000
But remember I went to school at Alabama State University so that we kept the group and so did the other two girls.

00:23:46.000 --> 00:23:55.000
And so we kept the group going during the time that we were fighting for a voter registration and that kind of thing.

00:23:55.000 --> 00:24:07.000
I may have mentioned that a lot of that was done by the youth because a lot of adults no longer wanted to participate for whatever their reasons were.

00:24:07.000 --> 00:24:23.000
So when James Bevel and those people came into Montgomery, they called on us to sing before the meetings that we would have in the rural areas as well as in the city of Montgomery.

00:24:23.000 --> 00:24:33.000
So we would travel around with them and we'd do the singing at the churches before the speech, of course, speak.

00:24:33.000 --> 00:24:40.000
So we kept our group, the Montgomery Gospel Trio, going up until that time.

00:24:40.000 --> 00:24:51.000
And after which I came to Atlanta, got with Bernice Johnson Reagon.

00:24:51.000 --> 00:24:55.000
It started, I guess, I have to back up to say that.

00:24:55.000 --> 00:25:03.000
She had asked that I participate in what they call the Pinnett Festival.

00:25:03.000 --> 00:25:19.000
And that's where the community and the school that was so much separation that they had found this Pinnett Festival to come together with the community to put on a performance each year.

00:25:19.000 --> 00:25:23.000
Yes, and I sneaked in that.

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:34.000
And when Bernice Johnson Reagon asked me to participate, we did the music for that first Pinnett Festival that we were doing.

00:25:34.000 --> 00:25:43.000
And after, I say, goodness, I have them singing and this was so good to participate in that kind of thing.

00:25:43.000 --> 00:25:59.000
But myself, along with another singer that was in the Harambee Singers, Matti Casey Pierce, Pierce Now, went to Bernice's house knocked on the door and said, we'd like to just continue to sing.

00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:02.000
Let's continue to sing.

00:26:02.000 --> 00:26:09.000
And thus far, we started the Harambee Singers.

00:26:09.000 --> 00:26:18.000
So I wasn't in that freedom group singers with Bernice, but in the Harambee Singers with Harry.

00:26:18.000 --> 00:26:19.000
Can you take you back?

00:26:19.000 --> 00:26:23.000
Tell me about, I don't want to ask about repertoire and what she most liked to sing.

00:26:23.000 --> 00:26:31.000
Like, saying the early in the gospel trio in Montgomery later in the, when you're college and then later with, how about that?

00:26:31.000 --> 00:26:35.000
It depended on what was happening at the time.

00:26:35.000 --> 00:26:56.000
That determined what we were seeing and what message we would, because we learned at Harlem that these songs, not only could care a message for the movement in Montgomery, but songs carry the message of the movement wherever.

00:26:56.000 --> 00:27:12.000
And that when we went to Harlem, we would sing in our songs, this little light of mine, which became one of the famous songs of the movement.

00:27:12.000 --> 00:27:25.000
And it's interesting to note that we were singing that for the movement at 11 years old and became one of the songs on the album there.

00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:30.000
We did, but that was one of the important songs we got.

00:27:30.000 --> 00:27:36.000
We are soldiers in the Army, was one of the songs we did, old freedom.

00:27:36.000 --> 00:27:42.000
So we were doing all of these songs at 11 years old for the movement.

00:27:42.000 --> 00:27:53.000
Songs which later became the bulk of the songs and the basis of the songs for that upcoming Civil Rights Movement.

00:27:54.000 --> 00:27:58.000
What part did you sing?

00:27:58.000 --> 00:28:03.000
I sang basically the melody, but we did interchange.

00:28:03.000 --> 00:28:10.000
And I do a lot of the lead singing on the song, the verse singing.

00:28:10.000 --> 00:28:13.000
Tell me about that work.

00:28:13.000 --> 00:28:25.000
I think with about 66, 1966 forward, the Harambee singers, and tell me about how that group evolved and you work there.

00:28:25.000 --> 00:28:28.000
I will.

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:42.000
I do want to say a bit more about how Linda and how our songs began to change as we attended those workshops with Guy Carawan and all.

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:47.000
If you go back to the songs, you will see that we were singing songs.

00:28:47.000 --> 00:28:49.000
Basically, we didn't like the song.

00:28:49.000 --> 00:28:59.000
There is a Montgomery song that represents that movement that was written by one of the professors at Alabama State.

00:28:59.000 --> 00:29:06.000
For me, for that era was the first actual song that was written for movement.

00:29:06.000 --> 00:29:13.000
And I like to get that in because people think it happened later on, but no right at that time.

00:29:13.000 --> 00:29:14.000
He wrote that song.

00:29:14.000 --> 00:29:24.000
But when we went to Highlander, we were singing some of the songs basically, the freedom songs basically as they were done traditionally.

00:29:24.000 --> 00:29:28.000
And we are traditional singers.

00:29:28.000 --> 00:29:35.000
And we would add a word in, in a verse or a line to represent our movement.

00:29:35.000 --> 00:29:39.000
Or sometimes we would change a line.

00:29:39.000 --> 00:29:48.000
But we weren't actually changing whole songs until actually we got there to Highlander and saw others do it.

00:29:48.000 --> 00:29:50.000
And then we thought we were equipped.

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:56.000
We were going back then writing songs and doing our own version of the songs.

00:29:56.000 --> 00:30:01.000
But we kept it traditional in terms of how we would sing the song.

00:30:01.000 --> 00:30:09.000
So if you hear our album or any of those things, you will see we kept traditional ways of doing that.

00:30:09.000 --> 00:30:17.000
If I wanted to add that because I wanted to get on the credit of how songs changed during the movement.

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:19.000
That kind of thing.

00:30:19.000 --> 00:30:20.000
Now what happened?

00:30:20.000 --> 00:30:23.000
In particular, what was that song that you wrote?

00:30:23.000 --> 00:30:25.000
There's one song that you wrote?

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:30.000
He wrote Ain't Gonna Ride No Buses No More".

00:30:30.000 --> 00:30:38.000
And it's interesting how he wrote that song, because sometimes now when I'm singing it, we are performing that song.

00:30:38.000 --> 00:30:41.000
People look and say, did you all say hell?

00:30:41.000 --> 00:30:43.000
Yes, that's the way he wrote the song.

00:30:43.000 --> 00:30:54.000
Because he wrote it from a traditional song that I think that that song is Angerad no More.

00:30:54.000 --> 00:31:02.000
And in that song it says, Highlander Hell, don't the white folks know we ain't going to ride them buses no More.

00:31:02.000 --> 00:31:10.000
And he said, Highlander Hell, don't the white folk know we ain't going to write them buses no More.

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:19.000
I have read two different accounts for how you are credited with adding a very important verse to we shall overcome.

00:31:19.000 --> 00:31:21.000
Can you share that to me with us?

00:31:21.000 --> 00:31:32.000
You know what? I don't know how much light I can place on that because you have to remember that I was at Highlander when I was probably 14 years old.

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:37.000
And we weren't thinking at the time, oh I said this, I did this.

00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:54.000
That was not upon our minds so that I can remember that when we went to Highlander, we had workshops to prepare us for different things that we would face.

00:31:54.000 --> 00:32:02.000
And one of the things that Reverend Solomon S. Seay Sr who drove us there said to us is that we are going to leave by night.

00:32:02.000 --> 00:32:13.000
And the reason for that is when you get into Monteagle and see the population of blacks, the population is just one.

00:32:13.000 --> 00:32:16.000
And that was September clock.

00:32:17.000 --> 00:32:24.000
And so to go in by night, we would not be noticed as we would go in.

00:32:24.000 --> 00:32:30.000
So we went there by night and we came back by night.

00:32:30.000 --> 00:32:38.000
But one of the things that happened when we were there is the policeman from the city came in.

00:32:38.000 --> 00:32:43.000
We were having a movie I believe that night, a song's best.

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:49.000
And they came in, they turned out all the lights from the city, they turned them out.

00:32:49.000 --> 00:32:54.000
So we were in complete darkness that night.

00:32:54.000 --> 00:33:00.000
And we could not see each other, we didn't know where I didn't know where my sister was.

00:33:00.000 --> 00:33:02.000
I didn't know where many were.

00:33:02.000 --> 00:33:08.000
And we were just there, wherever we were at the time when the lights went out.

00:33:08.000 --> 00:33:10.000
That's what we said.

00:33:10.000 --> 00:33:23.000
And so all these policemen came in and all we could see basically is the billet club, weighted and the butts that are gone, you could see it shining.

00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:33.000
And they told us to see if they could be quiet or whatever.

00:33:33.000 --> 00:33:49.000
And something said, We Are Not Afraid" verse of We Shall Overcome.

00:33:49.000 --> 00:33:56.000
And everybody started saying, we are not.

00:33:56.000 --> 00:33:59.000
And you could hear people coming in.

00:33:59.000 --> 00:34:07.000
My sister who is not a singer, I knew she was safe because I heard her out of tune voice coming in.

00:34:07.000 --> 00:34:13.000
And I could hear men's bass coming, about We Are Not Afraid" verse of We Shall Overcome.

00:34:13.000 --> 00:34:24.000
And we got louder and louder with singing that verse until one of the policemen came and he said to me,

00:34:24.000 --> 00:34:34.000
if you have to sing and he was actually shaken, do you have to sing so loud?

00:34:34.000 --> 00:34:37.000
And I could not believe it.

00:34:37.000 --> 00:34:48.000
And all these people had all the guns, the billi-cups, the power we thought.

00:34:48.000 --> 00:35:01.000
And he was asking me with a shake if I would not sing so loud.

00:35:01.000 --> 00:35:26.000
And it was that time that I really understood the power of our music, how powerful it was that this it unnerved him so much that he had to come and ask that I not sing so loud.

00:35:26.000 --> 00:35:33.000
And I could just tell you that I got louder and louder.

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:55.000
And somehow, even the nature out there in that darkness because everywhere was dark, but look like our voices blended that night to the point of complete harmony and beauty.

00:35:55.000 --> 00:36:05.000
And from then on, I knew exactly how powerful our song was.

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:15.000
Can you tell a story about singing in a particular place that really stand at a moment in a place that stands out in your memory very good of the game?

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:22.000
Now, that stands out, but there are a number of them, but I can say that we were in Montgomery.

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:26.000
I was in college at the time.

00:36:26.000 --> 00:36:33.000
And King was going to take us from his church.

00:36:33.000 --> 00:36:40.000
He was no longer living at the time, but he had come back for, I can't even remember what the movement was all about.

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:47.000
And we were going to march to the capital in Montgomery.

00:36:47.000 --> 00:37:06.000
And as we got to the top of the steps, and you saw all of these white people had, they had taken the mail to take it off their shirts, and they were just bare chested, standing up there with rifles and riding the horses.

00:37:06.000 --> 00:37:09.000
And I saw, I faced these horses coming down on you.

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:14.000
And when I got to the top of the steps, it made me sing that verse again.

00:37:14.000 --> 00:37:17.000
We Are Not Afraid" verse of We Shall Overcome, and we started singing it.

00:37:17.000 --> 00:37:31.000
Now, I can tell you that my knees were actually shaking that day when I looked out to see all of them, and we were going to try to march to the capital.

00:37:31.000 --> 00:37:37.000
But singing that song and that verse helped to count us steady those knees at that time.

00:37:37.000 --> 00:37:44.000
And I can remember that particular verse at that time and that particular movement.

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:48.000
Tell me, let's just shift for just a moment.

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:51.000
And I'm interested in your experience in college.

00:37:51.000 --> 00:38:01.000
Well, those college days were spent, as I said, SCLC had formed and sent James Bevel and James Orange into Montgomery.

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:14.000
And what we worked on at the time was voter registration again, even though I had handled voter registration at 12 years old with Mrs. Williams in Montgomery.

00:38:14.000 --> 00:38:24.000
And during my high school days, we just continued that whole thing of going to Kings Hill.

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:35.000
We ventured out into other places besides Montgomery, because Montgomery was so tight at that time after having gone through that Montgomery bus boycott.

00:38:35.000 --> 00:38:39.000
And the other thing we were working on was our sit-ins.

00:38:39.000 --> 00:38:49.000
And so we would go to the church and plan as you with James Bevel and James Orange, how we were going to go to the five-and-dime stores.

00:38:49.000 --> 00:39:04.000
And they told us at that time they had gone through training sessions on how to protect your head and that kind of thing and what happens if someone spits on you.

00:39:04.000 --> 00:39:10.000
And so, really they taught us nonviolence to a great extent.

00:39:10.000 --> 00:39:15.000
And so those were the kind of things that we worked on.

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:32.000
But let me just go back and say at 12 years old, in this Rosa Parks and Mrs. Williams, taught us how to fill out 27 page questionnaires.

00:39:32.000 --> 00:39:43.000
So that we could go into the homes of adults and teach them how to fill out those questions to become voters.

00:39:43.000 --> 00:39:45.000
That's what you had to do at the time.

00:39:45.000 --> 00:39:48.000
Just silly, stupid kinds of questions.

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:51.000
We had to learn the Preamble to the Constitution.

00:39:51.000 --> 00:39:56.000
But they set us on a little shop behind her house. She was our hairdresser.

00:39:56.000 --> 00:40:02.000
And the youth would go in there and sit on the floor and learn how to fill out these at 11.

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:07.000
Fill out these and answer the questions.

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:16.000
And we would knock on doors and teach adults how to fill out.

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:25.000
By the mid-60s, the subarides act has passed, by the mid-60s, but there's been tremendous violence and difficulty.

00:40:25.000 --> 00:40:31.000
And I'm thinking about the founding of the Harambee Singers.

00:40:31.000 --> 00:40:39.000
And how did you perspective at that time, say, 66 maybe compared to your perspective earlier in the 60s,

00:40:39.000 --> 00:40:49.000
or was your overall sense of feeling about the movement at that point in its progress and its challenges and its difficulties?

00:40:49.000 --> 00:40:59.000
Personally, I started paying more attention to, I guess, what we call Black Power and the Pan-African Movement.

00:40:59.000 --> 00:41:08.000
And so the songs that we performed as Harambee singers were what we call very radical type songs,

00:41:08.000 --> 00:41:13.000
We'll Move On Over You".

00:41:13.000 --> 00:41:20.000
And the songs took a different tone and became also international.

00:41:20.000 --> 00:41:24.000
We were very in tune to our heritage at the time.

00:41:24.000 --> 00:41:27.000
And as I said, Black Power.

00:41:27.000 --> 00:41:36.000
And so when we went, our hair was afroating, this kind of thing.

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:42.000
And our songs took on some of that same mentality at the time.

00:41:42.000 --> 00:41:51.000
So the Harambee singers song, we never did the songs that were performed by the Montgomery trio,

00:41:51.000 --> 00:41:57.000
but in fact, Pan-Africanist type songs.

00:41:57.000 --> 00:42:03.000
Can you tell me a little bit more about the groups repertoire?

00:42:03.000 --> 00:42:10.000
In terms of the songs, Hands Off Nkrumah" was one of the songs that we did because at that time,

00:42:10.000 --> 00:42:16.000
as I say, we had a Pan-Africanist perspective to what we were doing in the song.

00:42:16.000 --> 00:42:25.000
And so that was important to us as the movement was going on in Ghana.

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:31.000
We did do that song of Hands Off Nkrumah".

00:42:31.000 --> 00:42:36.000
That's what the people say, Hands Off Nkrumah".

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:40.000
And we talked about the CIA in the song.

00:42:40.000 --> 00:42:51.000
So we started tacking other elements of not only this country, but the world and what was happening.

00:42:51.000 --> 00:43:00.000
The things that want me to expand on things that already been said are just kind of things.

00:43:00.000 --> 00:43:02.000
Don't you?

00:43:02.000 --> 00:43:03.000
We've done pretty well.

00:43:03.000 --> 00:43:08.000
I didn't want to go back.

00:43:08.000 --> 00:43:17.000
Just ask about the question of whether or not your mother and your grandmother ever had to try to pull you and your sister

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:21.000
and brother back a little bit throughout a peer-free safety.

00:43:21.000 --> 00:43:24.000
Is that a good question?

00:43:24.000 --> 00:43:30.000
Yeah, but I'll start with our community and just say.

00:43:31.000 --> 00:43:37.000
Okay, we've had a short break and we're going to come back and talk to the board about family and community.

00:43:37.000 --> 00:43:40.000
Yes.

00:43:40.000 --> 00:43:51.000
Our community was filled with people who had participated in struggle in some type way.

00:43:51.000 --> 00:43:59.000
We had Flora Grant, who had one of the large debuts in Atlanta Life Insurance Company.

00:43:59.000 --> 00:44:16.000
And who kept herself close to movement things that's happening in the community, who would come to my home and sit with my mother to talk about those things as I sat under the table and they played cards.

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:29.000
But I would hear a lot at that time because she was very knowledgeable as to the kind of current things happening in the Montgomery community.

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:37.000
So we had Flora Grant and we had the young lady who wrote, see how they run.

00:44:37.000 --> 00:44:45.000
We had Sullivan Rogers, who was one of the first black jockeys.

00:44:45.000 --> 00:44:51.000
And we saw him train his horses and he would tell us stories.

00:44:51.000 --> 00:45:00.000
And we had my aunt who lived with us and her name we called her Besidee.

00:45:00.000 --> 00:45:09.000
Now Besidee was the storyteller in my family and she would tell us about all kinds of struggles.

00:45:09.000 --> 00:45:16.000
And the story that I remember from her was about the John".

00:45:16.000 --> 00:45:27.000
And when she talked about the John", she said that he worked hard from son up to son down to take care of his family, of the family.

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:36.000
But at the end of the day or the week, he had no meat, he had very little food.

00:45:36.000 --> 00:45:49.000
And it would bother him so much that he had taken care and raised the food for his owner as he sharecroped.

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:55.000
But he could not pay his bill at the end of the week.

00:45:55.000 --> 00:46:04.000
And so the John" found ways to ever so often get his family to chicken.

00:46:04.000 --> 00:46:18.000
And she told us the story of how John trained his younger son to come with him as they would get one chicken out of the white folks chicken coop.

00:46:18.000 --> 00:46:22.000
And he said, John, this night I'm going to teach you how to prize.

00:46:22.000 --> 00:46:28.000
And you're going to prize the chicken coop while I go on to get this one chicken.

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:38.000
Because there's something about black families that told them that they would get whatever was to survive but not more than that.

00:46:39.000 --> 00:46:44.000
And so he would get this one chicken for his family.

00:46:44.000 --> 00:46:50.000
So he carried a little John, I guess it was about the age of 12, I think she told us.

00:46:50.000 --> 00:46:56.000
And they would get this long stick to pry up the chicken coop.

00:46:56.000 --> 00:47:03.000
And this particular night, he was saying, Pry, boy".

00:47:03.000 --> 00:47:15.000
As John was shaking and almost to drop the chicken coop before John could get the chicken from the chicken coop.

00:47:15.000 --> 00:47:19.000
And he did with Pry, boy".

00:47:19.000 --> 00:47:27.000
And my aunt was just shaking all over in her voice so she was telling us the story about Pry, boy".

00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:33.000
And he dropped the chicken coop, could no longer hold it.

00:47:33.000 --> 00:47:39.000
And John said, right boy, go tell your mama, you're going to lose your prize.

00:47:39.000 --> 00:47:47.000
And so later on in life, from that story, I never forget that John could not feed his family,

00:47:47.000 --> 00:47:49.000
working from son up to son down it.

00:47:49.000 --> 00:47:56.000
Something in my hair did not set well with the fact that he couldn't feed his family.

00:47:56.000 --> 00:48:01.000
And that story, so later on I wrote a song that says, Pry, boy".

00:48:01.000 --> 00:48:03.000
Pry, boy".

00:48:03.000 --> 00:48:06.000
Pry, boy".

00:48:06.000 --> 00:48:08.000
Prize.

00:48:08.000 --> 00:48:10.000
Run fast.

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:16.000
Go tell your mama, John to lose his prize.

00:48:16.000 --> 00:48:25.000
So the people in the community, and as I say until young people, the song told us what you selected to do in life

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:27.000
will determine your life.

00:48:27.000 --> 00:48:30.000
And I think it was the song told of these people.

00:48:30.000 --> 00:48:39.000
And that impact on our lives that kept us even today, as I said here, 67 years old,

00:48:39.000 --> 00:48:45.000
still involved in fighting for freedom.

00:48:45.000 --> 00:48:48.000
So it's those kind of things.

00:48:48.000 --> 00:48:58.000
And I tell even seeing it today, I work with seniors that we have to keep ourselves close to the young people,

00:48:58.000 --> 00:49:08.000
causes the older people that had this impact in our lives that caused us to be the people that we are today.

00:49:08.000 --> 00:49:13.000
Really want to thank you for joining us this moment. It's been a real pleasure to be with you.

00:49:13.000 --> 00:49:15.000
Thank you.

00:49:15.000 --> 00:49:25.000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.
